<TITLE>Stephen Langlois</TITLE>

<PARAGRAPH>
<REF MENTION="1" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Stephen Langlois</REFEX></REF>
 is a Chicago area chef and co-author of Prairie: Cuisine from the Heartland (with 
<REF MENTION="1" SYNFUNC="obj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="1"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="1">Margaret Guthrie</REFEX></REF>
).
</PARAGRAPH>

<PARAGRAPH>
Currently executive chef of the Hyatt Lodge in Oak Brook, Illinois, 
<REF MENTION="2" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Langlois</REFEX></REF>
 was one of the chefs defining Midwestern cuisine in the 20th century. As chef of the now-closed Prairie in Chicago from 1986 to 1997, 
<REF MENTION="3" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 showcased strictly regional fare, even steering clear of ocean fish.
</PARAGRAPH>

<PARAGRAPH>
A graduate of the hospitality program at Triton College in River Grove, Illinois and the Culinary Institute of America in Hyde Park, New York, 
<REF MENTION="4" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Langlois</REFEX></REF>
 also worked at the Chicago restaurants Cafe D'Artagnan and Maxim's and the Pulitzer Hotel in Amsterdam, Netherlands.
</PARAGRAPH>
